  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping and reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n- Impose significant penalties for violations\n\n3. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n4. Penalties:\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Civil and criminal prosecution\n\n5. State-Level Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n\nThese statutes are designed to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities, which involve disguising the origins of illegally obtained money through complex financial transactions.",
